![](/images/kube/argocd_apps.png)

Now we're getting to the really fun stuff: GitOps.
The act of writing beautifully crafted `.yaml` files and see your Kubernetes cluster get red and stall out is surely what life's all about.

# Install ArgoCD

We have our Kubernetes cluster and now we're going to bootstrap ArgoCD so it starts syncing from our git repository.
Using helm:

```fish
helm install argocd \
    --repo https://argoproj.github.io/argo-helm \
    argo-cd \
    --namespace argocd \
    --create-namespace \
    --version 9.4.16
```

This will install ArgoCD under the `argocd` namespace and assign a fixed IP to it (so it's easy for the `argocd` command to find it).

ArgoCD will by default generate an admin password and you can get it with the `arcocd` tool:

```fish
# You can use the password to login to the web.
argocd admin initial-password -n argocd
# You can change the password like so:
argocd login 10.1.4.102 --insecure
argocd account update-password
```

And you should be able to login at `10.1.4.102`, the IP we fixed before.
You can verify the IP with this command:

```fish
kubectl get svc argocd-server -n argocd
```

To get the ball rolling we need to add a repository.
I use a self-hosted Forgejo instance internally at `git.hietala.xyz` but anything will do.
You need an API token with read permissions:

```fish
argocd repo add https://git.hietala.xyz/tree/home-ops.git --username admin --password token
```

Declarative setup: https://argo-cd.readthedocs.io/en/stable/operator-manual/declarative-setup/

```fish
kubectl create secret generic home-ops-repo \
  --namespace argocd \
  --from-literal=type=git \
  --from-literal=url=https://git.hietala.xyz/tree/home-ops.git \
  --from-literal=username=admin \
  --from-literal=password=2cfbfa5cc8cb0ada21333c729d0379517ef7d1e0 \
  --dry-run=client -o yaml \
  | kubeseal --cert infrastructure/sealed-secrets-cert.pem -o yaml \
  > gitops/bootstrap/argocd-repo-secret.yaml
```

We also need to add the repository label to the generated file:

```yaml
template:
  metadata:
    name: home-ops-repo
    namespace: argocd
    labels:
      argocd.argoproj.io/secret-type: repository
```

You can verify that the repo exists with `argocd repo list` or in the UI.

