# Planning a file structure

One of the benefits of ArgoCD is that you can create any kind of file structure.
That's also one of it's problems: it's hard to know where to start.

I found the blog post [How to Structure Your Argo CD Repositories Using Application Sets][]
illuminating and even though their setup is way overkill for my homelab I simplified their ideas into something that works fell for me.

The basic idea is this:

```
gitops
├── root.yaml                 # Level 1: Loads all files from bootstrap
├── bootstrap
│   ├── argocd.yaml           # ArgoCD can manage itself
│   ├── cilium_config.yaml    # We used this file when setting up Cilium
│   ├── appset.yaml           # Level 2: Loads everything under apps
│   └── ...
└── apps                      # Level 3: All our apps
    ├── authentik
    │   └── ...
    ├── miniflux
    │   └── ...
    └── ...
```

So ArgoCD will be bootstrapped with `root.yaml`, which will load everything under `bootstrap/`.
This includes our Cilium config we used previously, ArgoCD itself (yes, it can update itself), and `appset.yaml` which will create apps of all subfolders under `apps/`.

# App-of-apps and application sets

`root.yaml` will be a master "app-of-apps" as it will be an `Application` that spawns other applications.
It looks like this:

{path="gitops/root.yaml"}
```yaml
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: all-apps
  namespace: argocd
  annotations:
    argocd.argoproj.io/sync-wave: "-100"
  finalizers:
    - resources-finalizer.argocd.argoproj.io
spec:
  project: default
  source:
    repoURL: https://git.hietala.xyz/tree/home-ops.git
    targetRevision: master
    path: gitops/bootstrap
  destination:
    server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
    namespace: argocd
  syncPolicy:
    syncOptions:
      - CreateNamespace=true
    automated:
      prune: true
      selfHeal: true
```

You're going to see lots of yaml files like this, better get used to it.
The important bits are the name `all-apps`, it should be synced before everyone else (the `sync-wave` thing) and should load everything under `gitops/bootstrap` from my `home-ops` repo.

***

```
argocd admin initial-password -n argocd
argocd login 10.1.4.102 --insecure
argocd account update-password
```

```
argocd repo add https://git.hietala.xyz/tree/home-ops.git --username admin --password <pass>
```

```
argocd repo list
TYPE  NAME  REPO                                       INSECURE  OCI    LFS    CREDS  STATUS      MESSAGE  PROJECT
git         https://git.hietala.xyz/tree/home-ops.git  false     false  false  false  Successful
```

Then bootstrap the "app of apps" setup, which will load everything in `apps/`:

```
kubectl apply -f gitops/app-of-apps.yaml
```
# Renovate

![](/images/kube/renovate_bot.png)

Token with read/write permissions.

```
kubectl create secret generic renovate-token --namespace renovate --from-literal=RENOVATE_TOKEN=<token>
```

```
kubectl get secret renovate-token -n renovate -o jsonpath='{.data.RENOVATE_TOKEN}' | base64 -d
```

Test:

```
kubectl create job -n renovate --from=cronjob/renovate renovate-manual
```

You can also see logs with:

```
tree@winterfell ~/c/home-ops> kubectl logs -n renovate -l job-name=renovate-manual -f
```

And there's also a nice UI for this.

For the impatient:

```
kubectl annotate applications -n argocd --all argocd.argoproj.io/refresh=hard
```

[ExternalDNS]: https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/external-dns
[How to Structure Your Argo CD Repositories Using Application Sets]: https://codefresh.io/blog/how-to-structure-your-argo-cd-repositories-using-application-sets/
